  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed — the first 5 minutes are just waking up the legs. No pressure to hit pace yet.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic rhythm. Conversational pace throughout — you should be able to speak in full sentences without effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace in the final 5 minutes. A few minutes of light stretching afterward is a great investment.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond the easy first 5 minutes of the run itself. Keep it gentle.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing, then spend 5–10 minutes on light dynamic stretching — calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings especially given your Achilles history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the aerobic tone for the week. At VDOT 46.7, your easy range is 5:22–5:56/km — aim for the middle of that band today (around 5:39/km). The goal is active recovery and aerobic maintenance, not fitness building. If your legs feel heavy from the weekend long run, drift toward the slower end without guilt. This run earns its place by keeping your aerobic engine ticking over without adding meaningful fatigue.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to get blood flowing, then 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval effort with full recovery between each. This primes your neuromuscular system before the hard work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 × 1 km at interval pace (4:11/km). Each rep should feel controlled-hard — you're working, but not sprinting. Think 'comfortably uncomfortable.' If a rep feels easy, check your watch; if it feels desperate, back off 5 sec/km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m easy jog between each interval rep. Keep moving — don't stop completely. The recovery jog is part of the stimulus.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"1.5–2 km easy jog to flush the legs. This is non-negotiable — it accelerates lactate clearance and sets you up better for Thursday.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Spend 12 minutes on the warmup: 2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills (leg swings, high knees, ankle circles) and 4–6 short strides. Your Achilles will thank you for the thorough warmup before interval work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 1.5 km easy jog after the final interval. Follow with calf raises (eccentric, slow lowering) and gentle Achilles stretching — a small maintenance habit that pays dividends given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Tuesday's interval session is the week's primary quality stimulus. At VDOT 46.7, your interval pace is 4:11/km — this targets your VO2max, the ceiling of your aerobic engine. For a maintenance phase, the goal isn't to push this ceiling higher, but to keep it from drifting down. Five 1 km reps is a well-established, manageable dose. The key execution cue: each rep should feel the same. If rep 5 feels dramatically harder than rep 1, you went out too fast. Consistency across reps is the skill being trained here.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is a true recovery run — 5:56/km or slower is the target. If you feel the urge to push, remind yourself that the adaptation from yesterday's intervals happens during recovery, not during more hard work. Slower is better today.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. The entire run is at recovery effort — just ease into it from the first step.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes post-run. This is a great day for foam rolling the calves and a gentle Achilles tendon massage if it feels at all tight.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a deliberate recovery day. After Tuesday's interval session, your body is processing the training stress — this easy 6 km run promotes blood flow and active recovery without adding meaningful load. The science here is clear: running very easy the day after hard work accelerates recovery better than complete rest for trained runners. The temptation to run faster on recovery days is one of the most common mistakes advanced runners make. Protect this pace.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":53,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Include 2–3 minutes of dynamic drills — leg swings, ankle circles, and a couple of 20-second pickups at threshold effort to prime the system before the main block.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km). This should feel 'comfortably hard' — you could speak a word or two but not hold a conversation. If you find yourself gasping, ease back 5 sec/km. Threshold running is about sustained effort, not suffering.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to bring your heart rate down gradually. Avoid stopping abruptly after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog with dynamic drills. A couple of short pickups at threshold pace in the final minute of warmup help your body remember what 4:28/km feels like before you commit to 8 km of it.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy cooldown jog, then calf stretches and eccentric heel drops (3 × 15 reps, slow lowering). This is a consistent habit worth building given your Achilles history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's tempo run is the week's second quality session and targets your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain for roughly an hour at maximum effort. At VDOT 46.7, that's 4:28/km. In a maintenance phase, this session keeps your threshold sharp without the volume demands of a full build. Eight kilometers at threshold is a meaningful but manageable dose. The key distinction from interval work: threshold running is about sustained, controlled discomfort — not the sharp, high-intensity effort of Tuesday. Think of it as 'hard but in control' for the full 8 km.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Relaxed aerobic run at 5:22–5:39/km. Friday's run bridges the quality work of the week to Sunday's long run. Keep it honest — easy means easy.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Ease into the first kilometre gently.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes, then light stretching. Consider a short foam roll of the calves and quads to prepare for Sunday's long run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run serves a dual purpose: it maintains weekly volume and keeps the legs moving after Thursday's tempo without adding fatigue. At this point in the week, your body has absorbed two quality sessions — this run is about staying aerobically active, not adding stress. If Thursday felt particularly hard, it's completely reasonable to shorten this to 6 km or swap it for a rest day. Listening to that signal is good coaching, not weakness.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"40 minutes of low-impact cross-training at easy effort. Options: cycling, swimming, yoga, or light strength work (bodyweight squats, single-leg calf raises, hip bridges). Keep heart rate below 130 bpm. This is active recovery, not a workout.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of gentle movement to warm up joints before your chosen activity.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of easy movement to cool down, followed by full-body stretching with emphasis on calves, Achilles, and hip flexors.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a strategic rest-adjacent day before Sunday's long run. Cross-training keeps you moving without the impact load of running — this is especially valuable given your Achilles history, where maintaining calf and lower leg strength is a long-term protective investment. If you feel genuinely fatigued from the week, full rest is equally valid. The goal is to arrive at Sunday's long run with fresh legs, not to squeeze in extra work.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km very easy — treat this as your warmup. No pressure to hit pace. Let the body wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":100,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady 5:56/km for the bulk of the run. This is aerobic base work — the pace should feel sustainable and almost meditative. If you feel strong in the final 4–5 km, you may drift naturally toward 5:40/km, but don't chase it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 2 km at a noticeably easier effort. Finish feeling like you could have run further — that's the right long run execution.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup beyond the easy first 2 km of the run. Ensure you're well-hydrated before starting and have a fueling plan for anything over 75 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritize rehydration and a carbohydrate-protein snack within 30–45 minutes. Gentle stretching of calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors. Eccentric calf work (heel drops) is a good post-long-run habit for Achilles health.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the cornerstone of your week and the most important session for maintaining your aerobic base. At 20 km, you're holding the long run distance you've built — this is exactly right for a maintenance phase. The pace target is 5:56/km (the slower end of your easy range), which keeps the effort genuinely aerobic and allows full recovery before Tuesday's intervals. The most common long run mistake for experienced runners is drifting too fast — your fitness makes easy pace feel almost too easy, but that's the point. The adaptation here comes from time on feet, not pace. Fueling during the run (every 45–60 minutes) is worth practicing regardless of goal phase — it keeps the habit sharp for when you return to racing.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
